<br>
&quot;Aroorooroo!&quot;<br>
<br>
Ahnmei's fur bristled violently at the howl of warning. It saw her! She wasn't ready! She dug her feet into the dirt to spring back and away to safety. Too late for her. The alert was sounded and gnolls were coming at her from all directions. Too late indeed.<br>
<br>
Fade to black...<br>
<br>
A glimmer of light...<br>
<br>
Ahnmei opened an eye. She couldn't feel it, but the other was too caked with matted fur, mud, and blood to open. In the fuzziness that was her sight, all she could make out were swaying treetops slowly drifting by. She barely felt the soft grass that brushed against her fur. A low, rumbling growl that sounded unlike her own scratched her throat. Her pounding headache and nausea sent her reeling into the dark again.<br>
<br>
Waking into a nightmare...<br>
<br>
A loud cry of pain echoed throughout the apartment, which prompted a hasty rush of feet towards the sound. Ahnmei wept bitterly as the caregiver tried to comfort her. The Shir couldn't stand the pain; so much heat radiated from her body; her wounds screamed for soothing. Something thick filled her mouth and nose before her eyes rolled back into her head. The darkness embraced her again.<br>
<br>
Passing fancies...<br>
<br>
Images of Momma's smile, faint sounds of her laugh - pleasant passages of family time warmed Ahnmei's dreams. Momma brought her snout close to her daughter's and licked her nose playfully. Her tail wrapped around her waist as she danced with her kit. Momma pulled away as she waved and smiled. &quot;Bye bye, baby. Bye bye.&quot; She waved happily as Ahnmei tried to reach for her. &quot;Don't go, Momma! Please, Momma. Stay! Momma, don't leave me!&quot;<br>
<br>
Ahnmei woke with a start; both eyes open now. She shielded her swollen forehead from the blinding light of the moon. The treetops drifted by again, but the foliage was different. No grass brushed her fur either; this time it was weeds and small rocks. She tried to turn her head to see who was pulling her, but when she did, a sharp spike of heat raced down her side. She'd not try that again, by Vah! Still too weak, and still in pain, she could feel sleep coming back to visit. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ahnmei>Ahnmei</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/22/03 11:54:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=912.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Blessed by Spirits</span><hr size=1> “Ahnmei, dear, can you hear me?”<br>
<br>
Her eyelids slowly flickered open. “Mmmhmm. Wha…what happened?” She sat up cautiously, immediately placing her paw above her left eye, which was still tender and throbbing with warm soreness. The hazy black circle around her vision crept away as her sights centered on a massive fluff of gray fur. <br>
<br>
“It’s alright, dear. There, there. Easy now.” The elder Shir gave her the once over before handing her a cup of hot, medicinal tea. “You had quite a nasty run in with some gnolls. Again. I’m surprised you lived because…” His voice became distant as vivid images of growling, foaming-at-the-mouth dogs snapped and bit at her, mimicking in her mind the tale she was hearing. Just how did she manage to escape, she wondered. By the Spirits of Vah, there had been so many… <br>
<br>
She sipped her tea, trying to regain some composure to focus on what was being said. “You were lucky, gal. Had it not been for the Ranger passing through the burrow on his way to Halas, you’d have surely died.” He brushed some white flakes from the pale fur around her nose. “Drink it all. It should clear up the rest of your rabies.”<br>
<br>
Ahnmei’s lips curled around her cup into a quivering snarl. “Well that’s just great. Now I owe debt to a bloody Tunarian, tree hugging, Elf. He should’ve just let me go mad and die!” <br>
<br>
The elder chuckled quietly at the ruffled, young feline. “You must’ve gotten a much harder knock on that noggin of yours than I thought if you can’t tell an Elf from a Human. Now just calm yourself before you have another fit.” Ahnmei’s demeanor softened somewhat as she mumbled under her breath “Probably still a tree hugger. Trees are for scratching one’s back and sharpening claws. Everybody knows that.” She rolled her eyes and sipped up the last of her tea before lying back to have her dried wounds fussed over.  <br>
<br>
The elder drew in a deep breath as the now quiet Ahnmei flinched under his careful touch. His eyebrows pointed down into a sharp V. “Why were you even so far from home? If you want to kill dogs, there are plenty in the Moors.” <br>
<br>
Ahnmei’s voice was barely a whisper, “I thought they were weaker down there.” <br>
<br>
“Well it’s obvious they aren’t.” He sighed and kissed her head tenderly. “I know you want revenge, dear. I do, too, but you’re going to get yourself killed one day. This time, your mother’s spirit smiled upon you. Next time, and I know there will be a next time, she may not be there to help.”<br>
<br>
Ahnmei had heard similar speeches already, although before, she wasn’t nearly as hurt as this. Still, she disregarded the lecture just as she had all the others. It was her choice to hate mutts. It was her choice to kill them on sight. It was her choice to miss her mother so badly that she’d rather die than see another barking creature walk Norrath. Her mother didn’t have any choices, which was why Ahnmei’s heart filled with a deep seeded fury. They had to pay for their murder, and pay they would. Not even her mother’s paranormal plea for her daughter’s safety could keep the young Shir from seeking justice.<br>
<br>
When her wounds were freshly dressed, Ahnmei nuzzled under the covers to doze off. Her heavy eyelids blocked out the light and his voice began to trail off again. “Rest up all you can. You’ll need it. If you’re that adamant about your…mission, you’ll at least need some excelled training, new armors (now that your old ones are in shreds), and something better than a sharp stick. Thank Vah your mother’s spirit is active so she can watch over you and tell me what’s happening. I don’t know what I’d do if I lost you, too…” <br>
<br>
With a defiant snort and a weak “Love you, Papa”, Ahnmei was out for the count.<br>
